<body>

<div class="disclaimer-bar">
  <b>Independent analysis.</b> Built from publicly-available City of Toronto data — <b>not produced, reviewed, or endorsed by the City of Toronto, Toronto Police Service, or any government body.</b> Contains information licensed under the <a href="https://open.toronto.ca/open-data-license/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open Government Licence – Toronto</a>. See methodology and source links at the bottom of the page; any number on this page can be verified against the linked datasets.
</div>

<header class="hero">
  <div class="wrap">
    <h1>Did Toronto get faster after the speed-camera ban?</h1>
    <p>In November 2025 the Province of Ontario banned Automated Speed Enforcement cameras. This dashboard uses the City of Toronto's network of ~1,200 driver-feedback radar signs to track whether speeding actually rose — by street, by ward, month over month — with a 2024 control to filter out seasonal noise.</p>
    <p style="margin-top:14px"><a href="./story.html" style="color:#ffb4ab;border-bottom:1px solid rgba(255,180,171,0.6)">Read the short visual story →</a></p>
  </div>
</header>

<section class="wrap">
  <div class="kpis" id="kpis"></div>
</section>

<section class="wrap">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="head">
      <h2 style="margin:0">Total speeders, this year vs last year</h2>
      <span class="small" id="yoyWindow"></span>
    </div>
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:0" id="yoyBlurb"></p>
    <div class="yoy-tile-grid" id="yoyTiles"></div>
    <div style="margin-top:18px"><div id="yoyTierChart"></div></div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="wrap">
  <div class="card" id="spatialCard" style="display:none">
    <div class="head">
      <h2 style="margin:0">Speeding change by distance to the nearest ASE camera</h2>
      <span class="small">Spatial difference-in-differences · Jul–Oct vs Dec–Mar windows</span>
    </div>
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:0">A reader asked whether the analysis could be done <i>spatially</i> instead of just temporally. This grouping does exactly that, restricted to signs within 500&nbsp;m of a former ASE camera point — the zone where there's a plausible mechanistic association between a specific camera and a driver's speed. Beyond ~500&nbsp;m the "near vs far" framing breaks down (signs aren't being treated by any specific camera), so those bins are intentionally omitted. The DiD-adjusted bars also subtract the same windows in 2024 to strip seasonality. ASE locations published by the City include formerly-active and planned points; no install/removal dates are published, so "near" reads as "near a location designated for automated enforcement," not a guarantee enforcement was active.</p>
    <div id="spatialChart"></div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="wrap">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="head">
      <h2 style="margin:0">Streets with the largest jump in speeders</h2>
      <span class="tier-filter" id="yoyTierFilter">
        <button data-tier="10">10+ over</button>
        <button data-tier="20" class="active">20+ over</button>
        <button data-tier="30">30+ over</button>
      </span>
    </div>
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:0">Top 20 by <i>absolute increase</i> in vehicles measured at the selected over-the-limit threshold (Jan–Apr 2026 vs same period 2025). For each street: last year's count, this year's count, the raw increase, and the percent change. Click any bar to open the sign's detail panel.</p>
    <div id="yoyTopChart"></div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="wrap">
  <div class="chart-row">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="head">
        <h2 style="margin:0">% &gt;10 km/h over limit</h2>
        <span class="small">Volume-weighted, all signs</span>
      </div>
      <div id="cityChart"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="head">
        <h2 style="margin:0">Average daily traffic</h2>
        <span class="small">Vehicles measured per day, all signs</span>
      </div>
      <div class="mini-kpi" id="adtKpi"></div>
      <div id="cityAdtChart"></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="wrap">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="head">
      <h2 style="margin:0">Speed distribution — before vs after the ASE ban</h2>
      <span class="small">Share of vehicles in each 5 km/h speed bin · stacked windows</span>
    </div>
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:0">Each curve is the city-wide distribution of measured speeds during a 4-month window. A rightward shift means more drivers ended up in higher speed bins. The 2024 windows are included as a seasonal control: if the 2025 post-ban curve sits further right than the same-season 2024 curve, that's the camera-ban signature.</p>
    <div id="distChart"></div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="wrap">
  <div class="card" id="rtoCard" style="display:none">
    <div class="head">
      <h2 style="margin:0">A second question: did back-to-office mandates push downtown traffic up?</h2>
      <span class="small">Volume DiD · Apr–Oct 2024→2025 vs same windows 2023→2024</span>
    </div>
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:0">Ontario's Public Service was ordered back to office at 3 days/week effective <b>April 7, 2025</b> (federal Treasury Board mandate had landed earlier, in September 2024). To test whether the mandates measurably increased traffic, we compare the change in average daily volume at WYS signs in the 7 months <i>after</i> the OPS mandate (Apr–Oct 2025 vs Apr–Oct 2024) against the same year-over-year change in the prior year (Apr–Oct 2024 vs 2023) — a volume DiD.</p>
    <div class="rto-tiles" id="rtoTiles"></div>
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:14px">WYS signs sit in safety / school zones, not on commuter arterials, so this measures spillover onto monitored side-streets in each area — not the Gardiner or DVP directly. Confounders include the federal RTO already in effect for the baseline year, private-sector mandates, and changes in WYS sign coverage year-over-year (which is why we aggregate at the area level, not per ward).</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="wrap">
  <div class="card" id="cameraRankCard" style="display:none">
    <div class="head">
      <h2 style="margin:0">Former ASE camera locations ranked by speeding change nearby</h2>
      <span class="small">Top 25 · DiD-adjusted, signs within 500 m of each camera point</span>
    </div>
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:0">Each row is a specific Automated Speed Enforcement camera location, with the speeding change aggregated across WYS radar signs within 500 m of it. The DiD-adjusted column subtracts the same period in 2024 to strip seasonal noise. Reads "where did the camera-removal hit hardest, by individual former enforcement point."</p>
    <div id="cameraRankChart"></div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="wrap">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="head">
      <h2 style="margin:0">Map · ~1,200 radar signs · ASE camera locations</h2>
      <span class="small">Click any sign for detail. Toggle layers via the control top-right.</span>
    </div>
    <div id="map"></div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="wrap">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="head">
      <h2 style="margin:0">Streets with the biggest jump in speeding</h2>
      <span class="small">Top 20 signs by DiD-adjusted change · click to open</span>
    </div>
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:0">DiD-adjusted = (post-ban − pre-ban in 2025) minus the same delta in 2024, so seasonal trends cancel out. Positive bars indicate streets where speeding rose more than the seasonal pattern would predict.</p>
    <div id="moversChart"></div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="wrap">
  <h2>Wards by speeding increase</h2>
  <p class="small">All 25 wards, <b>ranked top-to-bottom by DiD-adjusted change</b> (post-ban Dec 2025–Mar 2026 vs pre-ban Jul–Oct 2025, with the same delta in 2024 subtracted to remove winter-vs-summer seasonality). The number badge is the rank. Click any card to expand.</p>
  <div class="ward-grid" id="wardGrid"></div>

  <div class="card panel" id="wardPanel" style="margin-top:18px">
    <div class="head">
      <h2 id="wardPanelTitle" style="margin:0"></h2>
      <span class="small" id="wardPanelMeta"></span>
    </div>
    <div id="wardChart"></div>
    <h3 style="margin-top:14px">Average daily traffic — this ward</h3>
    <div id="wardAdtChart"></div>
    <h3 style="margin-top:18px">Signs in this ward</h3>
    <div style="overflow-x:auto">
      <table id="wardTable">
        <thead><tr>
          <th data-sort="name">Location</th>
          <th data-sort="limit" class="num">Limit</th>
          <th data-sort="latest" class="num sorted">Latest %</th>
          <th data-sort="delta_2025" class="num">Δ 2025</th>
          <th data-sort="did" class="num">DiD-adj</th>
        </tr></thead>
        <tbody></tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card panel" id="signPanel" style="margin-top:18px">
    <div class="head">
      <h2 id="signPanelTitle" style="margin:0"></h2>
      <span class="small" id="signPanelMeta"></span>
    </div>
    <div id="signChart"></div>
    <h3 style="margin-top:14px">Average daily traffic at this sign</h3>
    <div id="signAdtChart"></div>
    <h3 style="margin-top:18px">Year over year — speeders by tier <span class="small" id="signYoyWindow"></span></h3>
    <div id="signYoyTable"></div>
    <h3 style="margin-top:18px">Latest month — speed distribution</h3>
    <div id="signBins"></div>
    <h3 style="margin-top:18px">Typical day pattern <span class="small">(2023 baseline · ~vehicles per hour)</span></h3>
    <div id="signHourChart"></div>
    <h3 style="margin-top:14px">By day of week <span class="small">(2023 baseline)</span></h3>
    <div id="signDowChart"></div>
  </div>
</section>

<footer>
  <div class="wrap">
    <h3>About this analysis</h3>
    <p>This dashboard is an <b>independent analysis</b> built from publicly-available open data. It is <b>not produced, reviewed, validated, or endorsed by the City of Toronto, Toronto Police Service, the Province of Ontario, or any government body or agency</b>.</p>
    <p><b>Provided strictly as-is.</b> No warranty, no guarantee of accuracy or completeness, no representation that the analysis is fit for any particular purpose, and no liability for any use made of it. Nothing on this page is professional, legal, traffic-engineering, or policy advice. The author takes no responsibility for downstream interpretation, citation, or republication, and accepts no obligation to respond to issues, correct errors, or maintain the page.</p>
    <p>All numbers on this page are derived deterministically from the source datasets linked below. Any reader can reproduce them by downloading the same files and applying the methodology described here. <b>Construction of the page and its analysis code was AI-assisted</b>; the data and the math are public and verifiable independently of the author or the tooling.</p>
    <p>No causal claim is made about <i>why</i> measured speeds changed. The difference-in-differences method controls for prior-year seasonality but cannot rule out other simultaneous factors (weather variation, road construction, fleet composition, post-pandemic travel patterns, demographic shifts, etc.).</p>
    <p><b>About the data's coverage:</b> the radar logs measurements 24 hours a day, 7 days a week — including overnight and weekends. The "Weekdays from 7 AM – 9 PM" schedule listed on almost every sign refers to when the LED <i>displays</i> your speed back to drivers (the visible feedback period), not when the underlying speed counts are collected. This was verified by cross-checking the City's hourly-archive dataset against the monthly summary: the monthly volume per sign matches the sum of all 24-hour, 7-day-a-week hourly readings to within ~1%. That said, the WYS signs are placed in safety zones and on streets the City has flagged for feedback — they are <i>not</i> a uniform random sample of all Toronto streets, and city-level totals should be read as "speeding on streets with WYS signs," not "speeding on every road in Toronto."</p>

    <h3>How the numbers are computed</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><b>"% &gt;10 km/h over the limit"</b>. For each monthly sign reading we sum vehicles in every 5&nbsp;km/h bin whose lower boundary is ≥ <code>posted_limit + 10</code> (e.g. for a 40 km/h zone, bins <code>spd_50</code> and above), then divide by total volume. Consistent across all signs.</li>
      <li><b>Year-over-year tier counts</b> ("Total speeders" card). Same per-row bin rule, applied for each tier (10+, 15+, 20+, 25+, 30+ over). City totals include only the <i>733 signs that reported in both Jan-Apr&nbsp;2025 and Jan-Apr&nbsp;2026</i>, so the comparison is apples-to-apples.</li>
      <li><b>Aggregation</b>: city and ward series are <i>volume-weighted</i> means across signs (a high-traffic arterial counts more than a quiet street). Per-sign series are direct monthly readings.</li>
      <li><b>Difference-in-differences (DiD)</b>: the post-ban window (Dec&nbsp;2025–Mar&nbsp;2026) minus the pre-ban window (Jul–Oct&nbsp;2025) — and the same delta in 2024 as a seasonal control — subtracted. <b>The DiD number is the honest headline</b>: it filters out year-over-year seasonality (winter weather, school sessions, etc.).</li>
      <li><b>Spatial DiD by distance to ASE camera</b>: signs are grouped into bins by great-circle distance (haversine) to their nearest published ASE camera point. The same pre/post 2025 windows are computed per bin (raw delta), and again with the 2024 control subtracted (DiD-adjusted). ASE locations as published include both formerly-active and planned points; the City does not publish install/removal dates, so "near an ASE camera" is best read as "near a location designated for automated enforcement at some point," not a guarantee enforcement was historically active.</li>
      <li><b>Sign relocation</b>: <code>sign_id</code> is intended to be stable, but a sign can occasionally be reassigned. Per-sign deltas on the most extreme outliers warrant a sanity-check against the address.</li>
      <li><b>ASE camera dataset</b> records current status only — Toronto does not publish install/removal dates. The Province's November&nbsp;2025 ban removed automated enforcement city-wide, not just at the points shown on the map.</li>
      <li><b>Hourly profiles</b> are a 2023 baseline. Toronto stopped publishing the detailed hourly archive after 2023, so the "typical day" charts cannot be updated to the post-ban era — they show each sign's pre-ban traffic pattern of life.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Verify any number on this page — direct dataset links</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Stationary WYS Monthly Summary &mdash; <a href="https://open.toronto.ca/dataset/safety-zone-watch-your-speed-program-monthly-summary/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">dataset</a> · <a href="https://ckan0.cf.opendata.inter.prod-toronto.ca/dataset/safety-zone-watch-your-speed-program-monthly-summary/resource/d098752f-8fa5-4c83-8ea3-6f9d29afdea9/download/wys-stationary-monthly-summary.csv" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CSV</a></li>
      <li>WYS Sign Locations &mdash; <a href="https://open.toronto.ca/dataset/school-safety-zone-watch-your-speed-program-locations/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">dataset</a> (GeoJSON / CSV options)</li>
      <li>Automated Speed Enforcement Locations &mdash; <a href="https://open.toronto.ca/dataset/automated-speed-enforcement-locations/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">dataset</a></li>
      <li>Detailed (hourly) Counts 2017–2023 &mdash; <a href="https://open.toronto.ca/dataset/school-safety-zone-watch-your-speed-program-detailed-speed-counts/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">dataset</a></li>
    </ul>

    <p class="small">Contains information licensed under the <a href="https://open.toronto.ca/open-data-license/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open Government Licence – Toronto</a>. Source datasets © City of Toronto. Page generated <span id="refreshedAt"></span>.</p>

    <p style="margin-top:24px;padding:14px 16px;border:1px solid var(--line);border-radius:8px;background:#fafbfd;font-size:13px;line-height:1.55">
